name: Imani Ellis
bio: founder & ceo of @theccnyc + @culturecon community organizer, NBC Alum, child of God

social_posts.post_text:
After a decade of transformation and exciting adventures, this week marks my last week at NBC.

I began my NBC journey ten years ago as a Page giving tours of 30 Rockefeller Plaza and today, am leaving as a Vice President. (Won’t he do it?!)

Working at NBC literally changed my life. I was blessed to work in my dream job with the most brilliant people. I am so grateful for this experience…I can’t begin to find the words, but I’ll try. 

Thank you to the best leader I could have ever asked for @jennjenng — for always supporting me and empowering me. We are 10 years strong of friendship and I will never forget all the incredible lessons you’ve taught me. I will be forever thankful for your mentorship and friendship. You are the absolute best. 

Thank you to @bravoandy — you are 1 of 1, a dear friend and mentor to me. I watch you in awe, marveling at your ability to do it all …and then do even more. I will miss you very much. Thank you @deeconnolly and @johnjude for your friendship, mentorship and support as I grew alongside WWHL, what an amazing ride we had! I love y’all! 

Thank you to my entire @nbcuniversal family for making the last decade truly unforgettable. Although I am embarking on a new path, I know that the purpose pulling me forward will light the way.

In my next chapter, I’ll be dedicating my full-time attention to creating Brave Spaces through @theccnyc & @culturecon — God has planted a mighty purpose on my heart & I am excited to continue building with my friends to see what comes next. Let’s goooo!!! 

Thank you @forbes for this feature & for your beautiful words @lydiatblanco 🫶🏾

Although @theccnyc began as an idea in my apartment, our community exploded online through Instagram —so it felt very full circle to moderate two panels at Meta House for my very first Art Basel! 

From building virtual spaces that provide therapy for grieving creatives to pushing the boundaries on what it means to even be a creative today, the talented panelists inspired me greatly.

Shout out to the incredible team behind #MetaHouse for creating such an intentional and vibe-y space for us!

Finally coming home to myself. I love it here.

New York City, you really are that girl. You took a timid little twenty-something & challenged her to become stronger day-by-day. You made it possible for a casual potluck to become a global community movement. We’re just getting started. Thank you @nycgo for sharing my NYC story.

Do you trust yourself? I recently sat down with @bimmawilliams for a really transparent conversation on how I’ve learned to trust my gut and what it means to be scared, but do it anyway. There is no such thing as a fearless warrior— and the reason you’re nervous is because it means so much to you. 🤍

The counterfeit innovator is wildly self-confident. The true innovator is probably scared to death. Scared because creative risk is as satisfying as it is terrifying— what if people don’t like it? What if that’s painful? The fear isn’t comfortable but it’s a good sign… it will make you diligent. Your ultimate goal should make any rational person tremble a bit. — The War of Art.

What happens within you during your transformation is far more greater than the final destination. @culturecon is a love letter to our community & our team is so honored to scale the intimacy we felt in my apartment to a global platform where you can show up as your whole self. // 📷 by my good sis @nvmwendy
cheers to all my fellow winter homebodies who are blooming right in time for Summer 🥹🌱

Community is going to be how the shift happens. We need each other — isn’t that wonderful? 

Thank you Los Angeles for allowing us to plant roots on the West Coast. @culturecon LA was truly special — I’ll find the words one day!

I realized I was tired. Not take a nap and keep going tired —- like creatively I can’t dream at the moment and need to sit still for a month tired. So I decided to do what James Baldwin did in 1948, I decided to go to Paris. I’ll be here for the month of July for my first ever creative residency— a dedicated time to think, play and rest. On my agenda? A full itinerary of new things & of course, a self-guided tour of all the places james baldwin frequented while he was here. thank you to everyone for sending all the recs. this trip is so unlike me, which is why I had to do it.

wrapping up part 1 of my creative residency (play!!) — I enjoyed a full James Baldwin-inspired week. I went to some of his favorite places (Brasserie Lipp, Cafe Le Flore, Shakespeare + Company & Les Deux Magots)— James’ ability to constantly explore himself and allow his story to guide his art and connect with others is what inspires me most. I have a few more days of play left before I move into Part II of my residency in the South of France where James did the one thing I still find hardest to master— sit still.

Part II of my creative residency (be still) was harder than Part I. Turns out play comes to me quite easily & being still, well, does not. 🙂 James came to the South of France in 1971. He went to Provence, I went to Marseilles. 

This past week, I challenged myself to spend more time in stillness, paying attention to my thoughts, desires, worries and hopes. It felt so great to give myself permission to relax. When I started to get restless, I came back to the fact that thinking and reflecting was the agenda— I wasn’t being lazy, rest is not earned. I also spent a good amount of time with my inner child, telling her I know things look new and scary sometimes, but we have more tools now than we had at 12 years old —- she’s safe! This time is flying by — I’m back in Paris now for Part III, Refine 🤌🏽 & I’ve been organizing everything to share, in case you want to plan out a mini creative residency of your own.

We should have more grace with ourselves. After all, we’ve been told that rest can always wait, but at what cost?

I followed James Baldwin to France, retracing his path to find a path back to myself. Isn’t it freeing to know that you can make mentors of people you’ll never meet? I’m still enjoying part three (refine) of my creative residency, shedding what I no longer need. I feel like I’ve turned a corner in my mind. I feel light and focused, playful and free. 

Organizing the three parts of my creative residency for you in case you need some creative spark of your own.

We have over 60,000 thoughts a day — but that doesn’t mean we have to believe them all. Coming out of my creative residency to see this interview is live was perfect timing. 🥹

Thank you so much for having me on @vaultempowers and @iambrandiharvey ! 🤍

Limited spots available! 🔗 in bio to RSVP

The old way wasn’t working anymore.  I had to confront my constant need to produce something, be something, do something. Sure, that hustle was necessary at times — but sustainable for all time? No. 

Since the Earth has been here longer than I — I’ll learn from her. And just as the Earth blooms and rests, so will I. A season for play, a season for stillness and a season for refinement — & also, realizing that these seasons look different for all of us. 

Thank you to @insiderbusiness and @joimariewrites who saw my Creative Residency & asked me to share my experience. & thank you James Baldwin. 

My friend @isisbreanna and I are co-creating something special to help you structure and guide your own creative residency/retreat. Join us virtually tomorrow at Office Hours to learn how to cure your creative burnout (link in bio to sign up!)

Have you ever felt stuck creativity? Earlier this year I had to take a break because I felt like I had lost my creative spark. Now I know that I can find pockets of peace throughout my day wherever I am so that I can come back to myself and my purpose over and over again. How do you get un-stuck and find inspiration?

I grew up playing by the rules, keeping my voice down and staying in my lane. As I continued to grow— the rules told me to keep quiet and to stay small. I’ve decided it’s time to reimagine my life on my own terms.

I’m honored to celebrate my fellow dreamers and rule-breakers with @jumpman23 — paying tribute to Michael Jordan’s 1984 historic game debut when he stepped on the court in those iconic pair of black & red Jordan’s even though they were banned to wear.

Jordan’s rule-breaking spirit has inspired me to build my life and dreams, my way. No risk? No reward. 

#Inmyjs #BannedDay

I spent four years plotting in my Vanderbilt dorm room, promising my younger self that all the late nights would add up to something more one day. Yesterday, I was inducted into the Vanderbilt Hall of Fame.

& as I spent the day walking the campus with my parents, all I could express was gratitude. Thank you mom & dad for giving me a dreamer’s heart. Thank you, Vanderbilt for pushing me out of my comfort zone. You can always go home again.

Walking into this birthday in awe of what happens when you start to see yourself as God and your community see you. I am the embodiment of all of the love that is poured into me and even if I stumble along the way, I know that my perspective has power and purpose. 

I want to thank my family, friends and entire community for this strong foundation on which I stand. Last year, I asked God to show me how good it could get & he whispered, “Watch This.”

📷 💕 @morrisde

Opened up an old notebook and found the first sketch of @theccnyc logo — scroll to see if you can find it 🥸. At the time, I was just searching for some kind of purpose but I didn’t know what I was looking for or where I would find it. 

Keep throwing things at the wall and keep searching, when it clicks, you’ll know. One day you’ll look back and see the searching was a part of the process, it makes you hungry. also, there’s something about notebooks — I have to write it down if I want it to be real.
